note_en:
If all  @sindresorhus modules are accepting  undefined as their input this will mean other users would need to do some unpleasant stuff to make it work when they have  null as a value in TypeScript. As pleasant as it would be to say people should start using only  undefined there are teams that would never agree on that.
 JavaScript API doesn&#39;t agree on this rule. What happens when one of your libraries accepts only  undefined but the JavaScript API actually returns  null.  document.querySelector() and  string.match() return  null. Will you make an exception or will you make the developer handle it? Both aren&#39;t very pleasant.
 I found a slight benefit of using  null in some use cases. Look at the example below:
 // this is a world case example from our own app:interface IState { dropLocation: string | null}function getDefaultState(): IState { return { dropLocation: null }}
 If the type  dropLocation is instead  string | undefined this would allow you to skip the  dropLocation declaration. This at first seems good right (less typing)? However, verbose code and fewer rules wins it for me. Verbose is good because you don&#39;t need to go to  IState definition to see what things are part of the state. Fewer rules because you don&#39;t need to decide whether you should add  dropLocation: undefined or not. That also means that every developer on the project won&#39;t need to go through the same thinking process.
